      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a6389b3a_d72b4cc0",
        "filename": "tests/GrSubmittedFlushTest.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 56,
      "author": {
        "id": 5036
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-26T13:07:23Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "So my inclination is just have the two states. The api just says that the callback is called when all work from the flush is submitted and the success says if there was an error. If the caller supplies semaphores that isn\u0027t considered \"no-work\". In that case the callback will not be called until GrContext::submit is called. So the only \"early\" successful call happens when there is no work on a surface to flush, no sync objects/requests, and no prepare for external stuff. Additionally it is a little weird that if you have no work to flush at all on a GrContext, then calling flush on the SkSurface work return \"nothing to do\", but calling flush on the GrContext would return \"success\" (cause we don\u0027t track work on a GrContext flush call).\n\nAs a side note, what do we think a client would do with a \"nothing to do\" return compared to a success return?",
      "parentUuid": "bc748895_c989f215",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 56,
        "startChar": 30,
        "endLine": 56,
        "endChar": 46
      },
